 P., Max Planck Institute for Chemistry, Atmospheric Chemistry Department, P.O. Box 3060, D-55020 Mainz, Germany; Juda-Rezler, K., Warsaw University of Technology, Faculty of Environmental Engineering, Nowowiejska 20, 00-653 Warsaw, Poland; Lelieveld, J., Max Planck Institute for Chemistry, Atmospheric Chemistry Department, P.O. Box 3060, D-55020 Mainz, Germany; Melas, D., Aristotle University of Thessaloniki, Physics Department, Thessaloniki, Greece; Rypdal, K., CICERO - Center for International Climate and Environmental Research Oslo, 0318 Oslo, Norway; Schmid, S., DLR, Institute of Vehicle Concepts, D-70569 Stuttgart, Germany","Emissions from land transport, and from road transport in particular, have significant impacts on the atmosphere and on climate change. This assessment gives an overview of past, present and future emissions from land transport, of their impacts on the atmospheric composition and air quality, on human health and climate change and on options for mitigation.In the past vehicle exhaust emission control has successfully reduced emissions of nitrogen oxides, carbon monoxide, volatile organic compounds and particulate matter. This contributed to improved air quality and reduced health impacts in industrialised countries. In developing countries however, pollutant emissions have been growing strongly, adversely affecting many populations. In addition, ozone and particulate matter change the radiative balance and hence contribute to global warming on shorter time scales. Latest knowledge on the magnitude of land transport's impact on global warming is reviewed here.In the future, road transport's emissions of these pollutants are expected to stagnate and then decrease globally. This will then help to improve the air quality notably in developing countries. On the contrary, emissions of carbon dioxide and of halocarbons from mobile air conditioners have been globally increasing and are further expected to grow. Consequently, road transport's impact on climate is gaining in importance. The expected efficiency improvements of vehicles and the introduction of biofuels will not be sufficient to offset the expected strong growth in both, passenger and freight transportation. Technical measures could offer a significant reduction potential, but strong interventions would be needed as markets do not initiate the necessary changes. Further reductions would need a resolute expansion of low-carbon fuels, a tripling of vehicle fuel efficiency and a stagnation in absolute transport volumes. Land transport will remain a key sector in climate change mitigation during the next decades. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Air pollution; Climate impacts; Emission scenarios; Emissions; Health impacts; Mitigation scenarios; Mobile air conditioners; Radiative forcing; Transport: road, rail, inland shipping; Vehicle technologies","Climate impacts; Emission scenario; Emissions; Health impacts; Mitigation scenarios; Mobile air conditioners; Radiative forcings; Transport: road, rail, inland shipping; Vehicle technologies; Air conditioning; Air quality; Atmospheric composition; Carbon dioxide; Carbon monoxide; Developing countries; Domestic appliances; Emission control; Environmental impact; Freight transportation; Fuels; Global warming; Halocarbons; Health; Nitric oxide; Nitrogen oxides; Ozone; Particulate emissions; Pollution; Roads and streets; Vehicles; Volatile organic compounds; Motor transportation; carbon monoxide; halocarbon; nitrogen oxide; air conditioning; air quality; atmospheric chemistry; atmospheric pollution; biofuel; carbon emission; carbon monoxide; climate effect; developing world; freight transport; global warming; industrialization; mitigation; nitrogen oxides; ozone; particulate matter; public health; radiative forcing; railway transport; road transport; traffic emission; volatile organic compound; air pollution; air pollution control; air quality; article; atmosphere; atmospheric pressure; climate; climate change; exhaust